      'The motion of an object released from a high place in a vacuum is observed. The variation of its velocity $v$ with time $t$ is recorded and the following graph is obtained.\n\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/eb3f57e7-c203-4906-83ba-9e90bed837aa/images/93def1d0-85b3-48b2-91f2-60218dac0567/Screenshot%202025-05-30%20at%209.27.44%E2%80%AFAM.JPEG)\n\n\n\n- Discuss the role that observations play in the development of scientific understanding. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n- Other than velocity and time, list two quantities that can be obtained from the graph. <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- \n  - The height of the release point is $70$ m. Show that the speed $v_1$ of the object just before the contact with the ground is $37$ m s$^{-1}$. <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n  - The object rebounds from the ground with a speed $v_2$ of $17$ m s$^{-1}$. The mass of the object is $8.0$ kg and the contact time during the rebound is $0.50$ s.\n    Calculate the average force acting on the object from the ground. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- They lead to the development of theories $\\checkmark$\n  \n  \n  - OR\n\n  They are used to construct or test a hypothesis $\\checkmark$\n  \n  \n  - OR\n\n  They are used to construct a mathematical relationship $\\checkmark$\n  \n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nObservations are fundamental for many parts of physics. They help to understand the behaviour of nature. According to observations, mathematical relationships can be obtained, a hypothesis can be constructed or tested and new theories can be developed.\n  \n- acceleration $\\checkmark$\n  displacement/distance $\\checkmark$\n  \n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nThe slope of the velocity-time graph is equal to acceleration and the area under the graph gives the displacement. Since the motion happens in one dimension and one direction, the magnitude of displacement and distance are the same. The distance can be also obtained.\n  \n- \n  - ${v_1}^2=0+(2)(-9.81)(-70)$ $\\checkmark$\nAccept using other uniform acceleration equations\n    ${\\ll v}_1=\\gg$37.06$\\ \\ll\\textrm{m s}^{-1}\\gg$ $\\checkmark$\n    \n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nThe object falls with an acceleration of $-9.81$ m s$^{-2}$ and it is released from rest. The speed of the object can be found from\n    \n    \n    - $v^2=u^2+2as$\n\n    where $u=0$ and $s=-70$ m\n    \n    \n    - ${v_1}^2=0+(2)(-9.81)(-70)$\n    - ${v_1}^2=0+(2)(-9.81)(-70)$\n    - $v_1=37.06$ m s$^{-1}$\n\n    \n  - $p_{before} = 296$ kg m$s^{-1}$ and $p_{after}=136$ kg m s$^{-1}$  $\\checkmark$\n    $\\Delta p =mv_2-\\ mv_1=136-\\left(-296\\right)=432$ kg m s$^{-1}$ $\\checkmark$\n    $F_{net} = \\dfrac{\\Delta p}{t}\\ =\\ \\dfrac{432}{0.50}\\ =\\ 864$ N $\\checkmark$\n    $F_N \\ll = F_{net}+mg=864+\\left(8\\right)\\left(9.81\\right)\\gg=$ 942 N $\\checkmark$\n    \n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nThe momentum of the object before the collision with the ground\n    \n    \n    - $p_{before}=mv_1=\\left(8\\right)\\left(-37\\right)=\\ -296$ kg m s$^{-1}$\n\n    The momentum of the object after the collision with the ground\n    \n    \n    - $p_{after}=mv_2=\\left(8\\right)\\left(17\\right)=136$ kg m s$^{-1}$\n\n    Change in momentum $\\Delta p$ of the object\n    \n    \n    - $\\Delta p=mv_2-\\ mv_1=136-\\left(-296\\right)=432$ kg m s$^{-1}$\n\n    The resultant force $F_{net}$ acting on the object during the  rebound\n    \n    \n    - $F_{net}=\\dfrac{\\Delta p}{t}\\ =\\ \\dfrac{432}{0.50}\\ =\\ 864$ N\n\n    During the collision, two forces act on the object: contact and weight. They are in opposite directions. Therefore, the resultant force $F_{net}$;\n    $\\begin{aligned}\n     F_{net} &= 864\\textrm{ N} \\\\\n     F_N-W &= 864\\textrm{ N} \\\\\n     F_N-mg &= 864\\textrm{ N} \\\\\n     F_N-\\left(8\\right)\\left(9.81\\right) &=864\\textrm{ N}\\\\\n     F_N\\ &=864+\\left(8\\right)\\left(9.81\\right)\\\\\n     F_N\\ &=942\\textrm{ N}\\\\\n     \\end{aligned}$\n    Note that the force from the ground accomplishes two things here: it exerts a net force on the ball that causes its change in momentum and it also counteracts the force of gravity that acts downwards on the ball.\n\n',
