      'The rotor ride in the amusement park consists of a vertical cylinder that rotates around its axis. Its floor drops down when it rotates fast enough, so that a person inside it is held against its walls. The walls are made of rubberized material such that the coefficient of static friction $\\mu <1$.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/6bc818c3-b41c-4cb7-a344-ddead3976ef0/images/281ae2f3-a2fa-4ee9-a300-6c714b1e0255/Screenshot%202025-06-02%20at%208.40.27%E2%80%AFAM.JPEG)\n\n\n$\\footnotesize{\\textrm{[Source: Image created using Images by  Clker-Free-Vector-Images from Pixabay - https://pixabay.com/]}}$\n\n- Explain in terms of forces how a person can remain suspended against the wall without falling when the floor is dropped. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- \n  - Show that the maximum period of rotation for the person to remain at rest relative to the wall is given by\n    $\\hspace{1em}$ $T=\\sqrt{\\dfrac{4\\pi^2\\mu r}{g}}$\n    Where\n$r$ = radius of the cylinder\n$\\mu$ = coefficient of static friction between the wall and the person <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n  - The radius of the rotor is 4.5 m and the coefficient of static friction of the walls is 0.40.\n    Calculate the angular speed of the cylinder necessary for this situation. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n\n- \n  - To make the ride more exciting, an idea of tilting the axis of the rotor by an angle $\\theta$ is discussed.\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/6bc818c3-b41c-4cb7-a344-ddead3976ef0/images/a0617516-bba2-4b35-88e7-31ebb403eb3d/Screenshot%202025-06-02%20at%208.38.35%E2%80%AFAM.JPEG)\n\n\n    Draw and label the free body diagram of a person at point A when the ride is in operation. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  - The cylinder is tilted a full 90$\\degree$ so that its axis of rotation is now horizontal. Deduce whether the minimum speed of rotation for this orientation is greater than or less than the minimum speed for the original situation with a vertical axis of rotation. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- The normal force provides the centripetal force, $\\checkmark$\n  Minimum speed is required / relation between normal force and linear speed. $\\checkmark$\n  Friction balances the weight. $\\checkmark$\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nThe friction force of the wall on the person is affected by the normal force\n  \n  \n  - $\\hspace{1em}$ $F_f=\\mu\\ F_N$\n\n  The normal force of the walls in this situation is the centripetal force, which means it is affected by the linear velocity\n  \n  \n  - $\\hspace{1em}$ $F_N=F_c=\\dfrac{mv^2}{r}$\n\n  This means that, there's a minimum speed at which the magnitude of the normal force will be enough so that the friction force of the walls will balance the weight of the person and keep it at rest without falling.\n  The person's weight is in equilibrium with the friction force of the wall.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/6bc818c3-b41c-4cb7-a344-ddead3976ef0/images/e2ca7f98-5e73-47f7-bb08-885c0300b78c/PH0651aaaa.png)\n\n\n  \n- \n  - $\\hspace{1.5em}$ $F_f=\\mu\\ F_N=\\mu\\dfrac{mv^2}{r}$ $\\checkmark$\n    \n    \n    - $F_f\\ = mg$ therefore $v^2=\\dfrac{rg}{\\mu}$ $\\checkmark$\n    - $T=\\dfrac{2\\pi r}{v} \\dfrac{v^2}{r} = \\dfrac{4 \\pi^{2r}}{T^2}$ $\\checkmark$\n\n    substitute and solve to get answer\n    \n    \n    - $\\ll\\ T=\\sqrt{\\dfrac{4\\pi^2\\mu r}{g}}\\gg $\n\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nThe normal force is the centripetal force\n    \n    \n    - $F_N=\\dfrac{mv^2}{r}$\n\n    And the friction force is given by\n    \n    \n    - $F_f=\\mu\\ F_N$\n\n    Then\n    \n    \n    - $F_f=\\mu\\dfrac{mv^2}{r}$\n\n    Since the friction force is in equilibrium with the weight\n    \n    \n    - $F_f=mg$\n\n    Then\n    $\\hspace{1em}$ $\\begin{aligned}\n    \\mu\\frac{mv^2}{r}\\ &=mg\\\\\n    \\mu\\frac{v^2}{r}\\ &=g\\\\\n    v^2\\ &=\\frac{rg}{\\mu}\\\\\n    v\\ &=\\sqrt{\\frac{rg}{\\mu}}\\\\\n    \\end{aligned}$\n    Since the linear speed is given by\n    \n    \n    - $v=\\dfrac{2\\pi r}{T}$\n\n    Then\n    \n    \n    - $T=\\dfrac{2\\pi r}{v}=2\\pi\\ r\\sqrt{\\dfrac{\\mu}{rg}}$\n    - $T=\\sqrt{\\dfrac{4\\pi^2\\mu r}{g}}$\n\n    OR\n    Since\n    \n    \n    - $\\dfrac{v^2}{r}=\\dfrac{4\\pi^2r}{T^2}$\n\n    Then\n    \n    \n    - $T^2=\\dfrac{4\\pi^2r^2}{v^2}=\\dfrac{4\\pi^2r^2\\mu}{rg}$\n    - $T=\\sqrt{\\dfrac{4\\pi^2\\mu r}{g}}$\n\n    \n  - \n    \n    - $T=\\ll\\sqrt{\\dfrac{\\left(4{)(\\pi}^2\\right)\\left(0.40\\right)\\left(4.5\\right)}{\\left(9.8\\right)}}\\gg=2.69\\ \\ll\\textrm{ s}\\gg$ $\\checkmark$\n    - $\\omega=\\ll\\dfrac{2\\pi}{T}\\gg$\n    - $\\omega=\\dfrac{2\\pi}{2.69}$ $\\checkmark$\n    - $\\omega=2.33\\ \\ll\\textrm{ rad s}^{-1}\\gg$ $\\checkmark$\n\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nThe angular speed is related to the linear speed by\n    \n    \n    - $v=\\omega\\ r$\n\n    And\n    \n    \n    - $v=\\dfrac{2\\pi r}{T}$\n\n    Then\n    \n    \n    - $\\omega=\\dfrac{2\\pi}{T}$\n\n    Since\n    \n    \n    - $T=\\sqrt{\\dfrac{4\\pi^2\\mu r}{g}}=\\sqrt{\\dfrac{\\left(4{)(\\pi}^2\\right)\\left(0.40\\right)\\left(4.5\\right)}{\\left(9.8\\right)}}=2.69$ s\n\n    Then\n    \n    \n    - $\\omega=\\dfrac{2\\pi}{2.69}=2.33$ rad s$^{-1}$\n\n    \n\n- \n  - Correct orientation AND labelling of vectors. $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/6bc818c3-b41c-4cb7-a344-ddead3976ef0/images/d79f0d1d-d21c-4838-8097-f4b718e5ff44/PH0651c_MS.png)\n\n\n    \n  - Horizontal axis of rotation: $v^2  = rg$ $\\checkmark$\n    Vertical axis of rotation: $v^2  = \\dfrac{(rg)}{\\mu}$  $\\checkmark$\n    $\\mu < 1$,\ntherefore vertical minimum speed is greater than the horizontal minimum speed of rotation. $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nFor the horizontal axis of rotation, the minimum speed occurs when the centripetal acceleration at the top of the motion is equal to the acceleration due to gravity, resulting in a normal force of zero.\n    \n    \n    - $\\dfrac{v^2}{r} = g$\n    - $v^2  = rg$\n\n    For the vertical axis,\n    \n    \n    - $\\dfrac{mv^2}{r} = F_N$\n    - $F_F = \\mu F_N = mg$ therefore $F_N= \\dfrac{mg}{\\mu}$\n\n    Which gives\n    \n    \n    - $\\dfrac{mv^2}{r} = \\dfrac{mg}{\\mu}$\n    - $v^2  = \\dfrac{(rg)}{\\mu}$\n\n    Because the question states that $\\mu < 1$\n    The minimum speed for the vertical rotational axis is greater than the minimum speed for the horizontal axis of rotation.\n\n",
