      'Three identical cylinders sit inside a cup. Their radius of each is 5 cm and their centres of mass are marked in the diagram. The lines connecting the centres of the masses pass through the contact points between the cylinders.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/75c1073f-1058-406c-9d31-7ea31814fde3/images/28eb4292-7e34-4dd1-b84e-523fa72ba475/Screenshot%202025-05-30%20at%209.33.38%E2%80%AFAM.JPEG)\n\n\n\n- Draw and label the free-body diagram for the cylinder $M_3$ <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/75c1073f-1058-406c-9d31-7ea31814fde3/images/8ceca09c-66d6-413b-a0a3-dbab45457fbd/PH0560-A.png)\n\n\n- \n  - For analysis purposes, the three cylinders can at times be considered as a single object consisting of the mass of the all cylinders. Explain why this simplification may be useful.  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  - The reaction force of the ground on $M_3$ is $30$ N. Show that the mass of each cylinder is around 1.0 kg. <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n\n- Determine the force that mass $M_3$ exerts on $M_1$ <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- $\\hspace{1em}$\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/75c1073f-1058-406c-9d31-7ea31814fde3/images/5079963b-144c-4400-ada3-9b1b31a00144/Screenshot%202025-05-30%20at%209.34.36%E2%80%AFAM.JPEG)\n\n\n  Correct direction and labeling of the forces $\\checkmark$\n  The reaction force of the ground is greater than the other forces $\\checkmark$\n  \n- \n  - Interactions  between the cylinders can be ignored/it allows only external forces to be analyzed  $\\checkmark$\n    \n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nEvery cylinder experiences forces due to their weights and forces from the other cylinders and the container walls. To decrease complexity in representing forces on the objects, the cylinders are simplified as combined to form one object so that forces between the cylinders can be ignored and only external forces can be considered.\n    \n  - Total weight of the cylinder = reaction of the ground on $M_3$\n    Weight of each cylinder = $\\dfrac{30}{3}=10\\ \\ll\\textrm{N}\\gg$ $\\checkmark$\n    \n    \n    - $m=\\ll\\dfrac{10}{9.81}=\\gg$       $1.02\\ \\ll\\textrm{kg}\\gg$ $\\checkmark$\n\n    \n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nWhen the three cylinders are considered as a single mass, the forces between the cylinders can be ignored. The vertical forces acting on the combined  masses are the weight $W_t$ of all discs and the R reaction force of the ground on the $M_3$.\n    \n    \n    - $W_t=R$\n    - $W_t=30$ N\n\n    Therefore, the weight of one disc $W$\n    \n    \n    - $W=\\dfrac{30}{3}=10$ N\n\n    So, the mass $m$ of one disc\n    \n    \n    - $m=\\dfrac{10}{9.81}=1.02$ kg\n\n    \n\n- The weight of the $M_1$ is balanced by the vertical component of the force from $M_3$ on $M_1$ $\\checkmark$\n  The reaction of $M_3$ on $M_1=\\ll\\dfrac{W}{\\cos\\theta}=\\dfrac{10}{0.87}=\\gg$ 11.5 N $\\checkmark$\n  OR\n  Reaction of the $M_3$ on the $M_1$ = Reaction of the $M_1$ on the $M_3$\n  AND\n  Reaction of the $M_2$ on the $M_3$ = Reaction of the $M_1$ on the $M_3$\n  Reaction=$\\ll\\dfrac{N-W}{2(\\cos\\theta)}=\\dfrac{30-10\\ }{\\left(2\\right)\\left(0.87\\right)}=\\gg11.5\\ \\ll\\textrm{N}\\gg$\n  \n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$: \nThe weight of $M_1$ is supported by the force of reaction $R_{31}$ of the $M_3$ on $M_1$. Therefore\n  $W(\\cos\\theta)=R_{31}$  where $\\theta$ is the angle shown on the diagram below.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/75c1073f-1058-406c-9d31-7ea31814fde3/images/8759817a-d2cf-403b-9d88-6f93199347be/Screenshot%202025-05-30%20at%209.48.31%E2%80%AFAM.JPEG)\n\n\n  The length L can be found with the Pythagoras theorem\n  \n  \n  - $L=\\sqrt{{10}^2-5^2}=8.7$ cm\n\n  Finding $\\cos\\theta$\n  \n  \n  - $\\cos\\theta=\\dfrac{8.67}{10}=0.87$\n  - $R_{31}=\\dfrac{W}{\\cos\\theta}$\n  - $R_{31}=\\dfrac{10}{0.87}=11.5$ N\n\n  \n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Alternative solution}}$: \nAccording to Newton's Third Law, the force of reaction $R_{31}$ of the $M_3$ on $M_1$ equals the force of the reaction  $R_{13}$ of the $M_1$ on $M_3$. The vertical component of the $R_{13}$ can be found with the help of geometry\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/75c1073f-1058-406c-9d31-7ea31814fde3/images/9338dc86-1aa1-47bc-9412-01f90ad79a7c/Screenshot%202025-05-30%20at%209.48.35%E2%80%AFAM.JPEG)\n\n\n  The length L can be found with the Pythagorean theorem\n  \n  \n  - $L=\\sqrt{{10}^2-5^2}=8.7$ cm\n\n  Finding $\\cos\\theta$\n  \n  \n  - $\\cos\\theta=\\dfrac{8.67}{10}=0.87$\n\n  According to Newton's Third Law, the force of reaction $R_{31}$ of the $M_3$ on $M_1$ equals the force of the reaction  $R_{13}$ of the $M_1$ on $M_3$. The vertical component of the $R_{13}$ can be found with the help of geometry\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/75c1073f-1058-406c-9d31-7ea31814fde3/images/fd3e2f7a-53c9-48d7-a7ce-91d39a71b611/Screenshot%202025-05-30%20at%209.34.36%E2%80%AF0AM.JPEG)\n\n\n  The reaction of $M_2$ on the $M_3$ and the reaction of $M_1$ on the $M_3$ must be equal to each other to cancel each other's horizontal components. $M_3$ is in equilibrium and vertical forces acting on cancel each other\n  \n  \n  - $2(R_{13})(cos\\theta)+W=N$\n  - $R_{13}=\\dfrac{N-W}{2(cos\\theta)}=\\dfrac{30-10\\ }{(2)(0.87)}=11.5\\ N$\n\n",
