      'A box of mass $3$ kg is placed on a box of mass $7$ kg. The coefficient of static friction between the surfaces of the boxes is 0.5. A horizontal force $F$ is applied to the $7$ kg box which sits on a frictionless surface.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/19ee0e9b-367f-408b-871c-526728275c32/images/452f270b-6451-4959-b170-f51f3cf61e4b/PH0549.png)\n\n\nWhat is the maximum value of $F$ that can move the boxes without the $3$ kg box slipping?\n\n\n- A. $\\hspace{1em}$  1 N\n- B. $\\hspace{1em}$  5 N\n- C. $\\hspace{1em}$  10 N\n- D. $\\hspace{1em}$  50 N\n',
    markScheme:
      "D\n\n$\\underline{\\textrm{Explanation}}$:\nThe free-body diagrams of the boxes:\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/19ee0e9b-367f-408b-871c-526728275c32/images/9d860ecd-59e5-4504-b19f-2b1efaf7504f/Screenshot%202025-07-08%20at%205.51.14%E2%80%AFPM.png)\n\n\nNote that it is friction from the bottom box that provides the net force that accelerates the $3$ kg box, and this same force of friction pulls backwards on the $7$ kg box.\nThe maximum value of the force of friction $F_f$ can be calculated as follows;\n\n\n- $F_f=\\mu_s F_N=\\mu_s mg=(0.5)(3)g=1.5g = 15$ N\n\nWhen Newton's Second Law is applied to the mass of $3$ kg;\n\n\n- $F_{net}=ma$\n- $1.5g=3a$\n- $0.5g=a$\n\nTo move without slipping, both of the masses must have the same acceleration. Treating both boxes as one system\n\n\n- $F_{net}=ma$\n- $F_{net}=(10)(0.5g)$\n- $F=5(10)=50$ N\n\nHence, the correct answer is D.",
